  "text": "Stargardt disease, which affects cones and rods, is most often manifested in early-onset macular degeneration. In Abca4 −/− mice, a model of the most common human recessive Stargardt disease, intraocular administration of an AAV encoding ABCA4 resulted in protein localization to rod outer segments and stable morphological and functional improvement of the phenotype in one study [CITATION_1] . The large size of the ABCA4 gene (∼7 kb) led other groups to use LVs. In the same mouse www.annualreviews.org • Gene Therapy for Blindnessmodel, LVs ensured high transduction efficiency in rods and cones and significant reduction of lipofuscin pigment A2E accumulation, suggesting that LV gene therapy is potentially an efficient tool to treat ABCA4-associated diseases [CITATION_2] ).",
